  "cells": [
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "Method\n",
        "We used tabular Q-learning in the stochastic windy gridworld, and compared two exploration policies:\n",
        "\n",
        "\\(\\epsilon\\)-greedy\n",
        "Softmax (Boltzmann) with temperature \\(\\tau\\)\n",
        "The Q-update used in both cases is:\n",
        "\n",
        "\

\[ Q(s_t,a_t) \\leftarrow Q(s_t,a_t) + \\alpha \\Big[ r_{t+1} + \\gamma \\max_{a'} Q(s_{t+1},a') - Q(s_t,a_t) \\Big] \\]

\n",
        "\n",
        "with terminal handling:\n",
        "\n",
        "\

\[ \\max_{a'} Q(s_{t+1},a') = 0 \\quad \\text{if } done = \\text{True}. \\]

\n",
        "\n",
        "Exploration policies:\n",
        "\n",
        "\

\[ \\pi_{\\epsilon}(a \\mid s) =\n",
        "\\begin{cases}\n",
        "1 - \\epsilon + \\dfrac{\\epsilon}{|A|}, & a = \\arg\\max_b Q(s,b) \\\\\n",
        "\\dfrac{\\epsilon}{|A|}, & \\text{otherwise}\n",
        "\\end{cases} \\]

\n",
        "\n",
        "\

\[ \\pi_{\\tau}(a \\mid s) = \\dfrac{\\exp\\big(Q(s,a)/\\tau\\big)}{\\sum_b \\exp\\big(Q(s,b)/\\tau\\big)} \\]

\n",
        "\n",
        "Algorithm (Q-learning with selectable exploration)\n",
        "Initialize \\(Q(s,a)=0\\) for all \\((s,a)\\)\n",
        "For each timestep:\n",
        "choose action \\(a_t\\) from either \\(\\epsilon\\)-greedy or softmax policy\n",
        "execute \\(a_t\\), observe \\((r_{t+1}, s_{t+1}, done)\\)\n",
        "update \\(Q(s_t,a_t)\\) with the equation above\n",
        "if terminal: reset environment\n",
        "\n",
        "Comparison Figure\n",
        "Include one plot with average return vs timesteps (averaged over repetitions), containing:\n",
        "\n",
        "\\(\\epsilon\\)-greedy curves for several \\(\\epsilon\\) values (e.g., 0.01, 0.1, 0.3)\n",
        "softmax curves for several \\(\\tau\\) values (e.g., 0.01, 0.1, 1.0)\n",
        "\n",
        "Caption example:\n",
        "\"Comparison of exploration strategies in stochastic windy gridworld. Curves are averaged over \\(N\\) repetitions and smoothed with window \\(w\\).\"\n",
        "\n",
        "Interpretation\n",
        "Small \\(\\epsilon\\) or small \\(\\tau\\): faster exploitation, but risk of insufficient exploration.\n",
        "Large \\(\\epsilon\\) or large \\(\\tau\\): more exploration, but slower convergence.\n",
        "In our runs, the best performance was obtained at moderate exploration (replace with your best setting: \\(\\epsilon=\\dots\\) or \\(\\tau=\\dots\\)).\n",
        "\n",
        "Preferred method:\n",
        "I prefer softmax when I want smoother, value-sensitive exploration (actions with higher \\(Q\\) are sampled more often, not just greedy vs random).\n",
        "I prefer \\(\\epsilon\\)-greedy when simplicity and speed are more important.\n",
        "\n",
        "RL vs Dynamic Programming optimum\n",
        "RL may approach DP performance, but often does not exactly match it in finite training because:\n",
        "\n",
        "finite samples (not full model access),\n",
        "stochastic transitions/wind,\n",
        "exploration noise during learning,\n",
        "hyperparameter sensitivity \\((\\alpha,\\epsilon,\\tau)\\),\n",
        "possible non-convergence in limited time.\n",
        "\n",
        "So DP is typically the reference upper bound (with full model), while model-free RL is a sample-based approximation that can get close but may remain below it.\n"
      ]
    }
  ],
